{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0196niAaQsBje4bx8Zi6ee7b","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive view of the failures. Let me analyze the patterns:\n\n## Failure Categories\n\n### 1. Title split across two lines (title not reconstructable)\n- **Żur Żytni**: `Żur` on line 1, `żytni` on line 2. The 2-line join would be `Żur żytni` but the expected is `Żur Żytni`. Also `żytni` starts with lowercase, which means `isLikelyGarbled` would reject it (\"`/^[a-z]/.test(text.trim())`\"). But `Żur żytni` as a 2-line join has `żytni` starting with lowercase in the 2nd word but the 2-line join `Żur żytni` starts with `Ż` (uppercase) so it would pass the `^[a-z]` test. BUT: the multi-word hasGarbledWord check: \"`żytni`\" - starts with lowercase `ż`, has `w\n\nI'm checking whether the regex patterns correctly handle Polish characters like `ż` when testing for garbled text, since the character class `[a-z]` in JavaScript doesn't match accented letters. So `ż` gets stripped out by the regex that only captures ASCII letters, leaving `ytni` with 4 characters—which exceeds the 3-letter threshold. The vowel check then looks at just the `i`, giving a low vowel ratio that likely doesn't trigger the garbled detection either.\n\nThe real issue is that the algorithm produces `Żur żytni` with mixed casing, but the expected output is `Żur Żytni` with consistent capitalization. Since the source file has lowercase `ż` on the second line, the algorithm can't generate the properly capitalized version—this is fundamentally a case-normalization problem. I'm checking whether `Żur` alone gets filtered by the garbled word logic—it has only 2 letters after removing the special character, so that might trigger the filter, but I need to verify the exact conditions. Looking at the test failures more carefully, I need to understand what the algorithm is actually returning versus what's expected. The results file doesn't show the actual output, just that these cases failed. Let me trace through what happens with each file — starting with `BARSZCZ`, which is all caps on the first line and should normalize to `Barszcz`.\n\nThe algorithm checks if it's a structural heading (requires at least 2 words), so the single all-caps word doesn't qualify there. The all-caps bonus alone is only 0.03, which seems too weak. Meanwhile, the body text below gets marked as garbled due to the sentence structure, so `BARSZCZ` should emerge as the best candidate — but the expected output is title-cased, not all-caps, which suggests the algorithm might be returning the raw `BARSZCZ` instead of normalizing it. I'm noticing that other ALL_CAPS titles like `ARAYES SHRAK` and `KREM SELEROWY Z GORGONZOLA` pass their tests with uppercase preserved, so the issue isn't simply about case normalization across the board. The real problem is that the OCR output has `BARSZCZ` in all caps, but the expected test value is `Barszcz` in title case—a mismatch between what the OCR file contains and what the test expects.\n\nThis points to a test data inconsistency rather than an algorithm flaw, though the algorithm itself doesn't handle case normalization, which means it fails the exact string comparison even though it extracted the correct content. Looking at the second case with Beef Stew, the first line gets correctly filtered out by the pipe character check, leaving `BEEF STEW` as the candidate title.\n\nBut again, the expected output is `Beef Stew` in title case, not all caps. The same pattern repeats across multiple recipes—Mushroom Pasta comes through as `MUSHROOM PASTA`, Paella Valenciana gets merged from two all-caps lines into `PAELLA VALENCIANA`, and Makowiec follows the same all-caps format. Every single one of these is failing the test because the algorithm isn't converting the extracted text to proper title case.\n\nNow looking at the Makowiec case more carefully—the line `MAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake)` actually fails the all-caps check since the words in parentheses have lowercase letters mixed in. So it would pass through as a candidate, but the real issue is whether it gets truncated at the parentheses or kept whole, and either way it's still not being converted to title case like the test expects. I'm seeing a pattern here—both cases have the same core issues. The algorithm is pulling in the full line with parenthetical descriptions, but the expected output wants just the recipe name in proper title case. So `ŻUREK (Polish Sour Rye Soup)` should extract to just `Żurek`, stripping both the ALL_CAPS formatting and the parenthetical subtitle. This is a consistent over-extraction problem across multiple entries. ### Case 7: **Piernik**\nFile has a \"POPRZEDNIA STRONA - SZUM OCR:\" section at top with garbled content, then `PIERNIK (Polish Gingerbread)` at line 21.\nExpected: `Piernik`\nSame issue: returns `PIERNIK (Polish Gingerbread)` but expected `Piernik`. ALL_CAPS + parenthetical.\n\n### Case 8: **Żur Żytni**\nFile starts with: `Żur` (line 1), `żytni` (line 2).\nExpected: `Żur Żytni`.\n`Żur` alone gets filtered as garbled since it has only 2 ASCII letters and isn't in the common short words list. When the two lines join as `Żur żytni`, the garbled word check passes because neither word starts with ASCII lowercase, but the result comes out as all lowercase `ż` instead of the expected title case.\n\nSo the core issues are: single-word garbling filters are too aggressive, ALL_CAPS detection isn't normalizing properly, and case handling for non-ASCII characters needs work. Checking the vowel ratio for `urytni` — that's 3 vowels out of 6 letters, which falls within the acceptable range. The string doesn't have a single word with 3 or fewer letters, no internal case transitions, and doesn't start with a lowercase letter, so it passes those checks too.\n\nFor the multi-word validation, I'm checking each word against the garbled word pattern — neither \"Żur\" nor \"żytni\" start with ASCII lowercase letters, so that passes as well. The phrase clears the hard filters, but there's a case mismatch: it's `Żur żytni` when it should be `Żur Żytni`. That's the normalization issue here.\n\nNow moving to the next case with \"Zupy Zimowe Warzywne\"...\n\nLooking at `Zupy` on its own, I'm extracting just the letters to check if it's garbled. The word has 4 characters total with a vowel ratio of 0.5, so it doesn't trigger the garbled detection on vowel count alone. I need to check for the pattern where lowercase letters are followed by uppercase ones.\n\nNow I'm realizing `Zupy` is actually in the section labels list. When I normalize it by stripping diacritics, converting to lowercase, and removing trailing punctuation, I get `\"zupy\"` which matches an entry in `SECTION_LABELS`. So this word gets filtered out as a section label rather than treated as content. The filtering logic checks the first line to determine whether to join multiple lines together.\n\nSince `Zupy` is identified as a section label, the code skips the 2-line join that would create `Zupy Zimowe`, and also skips the 3-line join for `Zupy Zimowe Warzywne`. But in this particular file, that full three-word phrase is actually the recipe title, not a section header. The real issue is that `\"zupy\"` shouldn't be in `SECTION_LABELS` as a standalone entry when it's part of a longer recipe name.\n\nNow I'm looking at another pattern with files like Coleslaw and Beet Salad that have `SEZON: WIOSNA` at the top—I need to check whether that header interferes with title detection.\n\nLet me trace through the validation: `SEZON: WIOSNA` passes the garbled check (11 letters with decent vowel ratio), and when normalized and stripped of trailing punctuation, it doesn't match any section labels and doesn't contain pipes or multiple slashes, so it won't be filtered out as a section header.\n\nNow I'm checking if it qualifies as a structural heading—it's all caps with two words, but I need to verify whether each significant word has at least four letters to meet that criteria. So the issue is that `BEEF STEW` gets flagged as a structural heading because it's all caps and positioned early, when the expected output should be the properly cased `Beef Stew`. And looking at `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION`, the same pattern emerges—the algorithm is treating these all-caps recipe names as structural headings rather than actual titles.\n\nThe multi-title detection is kicking in because there are multiple all-caps candidates, so it's checking whether the non-first ones are sub-headers. Let me trace through what's happening with the sorting and filtering logic to see where the algorithm is going wrong. HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION`. That should return the correct answer.\n\nBut it fails! So maybe the dedup or multi-title logic isn't working as described. Or maybe there's a different issue.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the pre-structural heading continuation logic. I'm checking if `baseHeading` matches a structural heading pattern where the text starts with the base heading followed by specific punctuation like slashes, ampersands, or colons. This logic would select the first heading that fits this pattern, or fall back to `baseHeading` if none do.\n\nThe issue might be that `baseHeading` itself is selected by embedding score, so `HERB BAKED SALMON` could rank higher than the full `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` because it's cleaner. If that's the case, then the continuation check would look for candidates starting with \"herb baked salmon \" followed by those special characters.\n\n`HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` fits perfectly—after removing \"herb baked salmon \", the remainder is `+ DILL SAUCE VARIATION`, which starts with `+`. So the algorithm upgrades `firstStructuralHeading` to the full variation and applies the structural bonus to it. Then there's a filtering step that removes any selected candidates that are prefixes of the structural heading.\n\nFiltering selected candidates... Checking the logic for detecting whether `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` is followed by ingredients—the code looks ahead a few lines and finds that line 33 is empty, line 34 says `Ingredients:` (which doesn't match the ingredient pattern), and line 35 has `- 1 cup Greek yogurt` which does trigger the ingredient detection.\n\nSo the algorithm correctly identifies `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` as a subheader followed by ingredients, making it part of the selected group. But the test is still failing, which suggests the actual output might be slightly different from what I expect—maybe the algorithm is returning just the first header `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` from line 1 instead of grouping it with the separate `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` section that appears later.\n\nWait, I think I see the real problem now. The dedup filter is removing `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` because it contains both `HERB BAKED SALMON` and `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` as substrings, and those shorter strings are also in the selected array. So the dedup logic would eliminate the combined header, leaving only the individual components. Oh right, there's a prefix removal step that runs before deduplication. The full title `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` gets marked as the first structural heading, and then any shorter heading that appears as a prefix of it gets filtered out. So `HERB BAKED SALMON` would be removed here because it's a prefix of the full title, leaving just the complete version.\n\nAfter that filtering, I'm left with the full title and `DILL SAUCE VARIATION`. Then there's a sub-section pre-dedup filter that checks if an all-caps candidate is followed by ingredients in the source lines, and if so, whether there's a longer parent heading that would make it redundant.\n\nFor `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` at position 0, the next line is empty, so it passes. For `DILL SAUCE VARIATION` around position 32, the next line is `Ingredients:` which doesn't look like an ingredient itself, but checking just that one line ahead (not two), there's no ingredient immediately following, so it also passes the filter.\n\nDuring deduplication, the longer title `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` gets removed because it contains the shorter `DILL SAUCE VARIATION`, leaving only the shorter one. Then the multi-title guard kicks in with this single ALL_CAPS item appearing late in the document.\n\nThe relative position is 32 out of roughly 53 lines, which is 0.60—well below the 0.75 threshold for the last quarter of the document, so it passes through and returns `DILL SAUCE VARIATION`. But the expected output is the full compound title, which reveals the core issue: when a compound title from the beginning contains a subtitle that appears later, the dedup logic incorrectly removes the full title instead of preserving it.\n\nNow looking at the Placki Serowe example, `PLACKI SEROWE` is all caps with two words of four letters or more, which marks it as a structural heading. The word `placki` does appear in the section labels list, but the full phrase `placki serowe` doesn't, so it passes the section label check. The real problem is the case mismatch—the algorithm returns the uppercase version when it should normalize to title case. I'm seeing the pattern now—the test failures split into two categories: cases where the algorithm returns completely wrong content, and cases where it finds the right recipe but returns it in ALL_CAPS when the expected format is Title Case. The inconsistency is that some tests expect ALL_CAPS results and pass, while others expect Title Case and fail even though the algorithm correctly identifies the recipe. So `PLACKI SEROWE` gets marked as wrong when the expected is `Placki Serowe`, even though the content match is correct. I'm overcomplicating this. Let me just look at what the algorithm actually produces versus what's expected, without getting caught up in the reasoning behind the test cases. The real issue is straightforward: I'm seeing a clear pattern where ALL_CAPS input titles aren't being converted to Title Case the way the tests expect, and I should categorize these failures to understand the scope of the problem. I'm checking why \"Roasted Beet and Goat Cheese Salad\" fails the garbled text filter even though it has a good vowel ratio and proper mixed case formatting—ah, I see the issue now: there's an internal lowercase-to-uppercase transition that triggers the garbled detection, which is causing the false positive. All the individual words pass the garbled check, so the title qualifies as a candidate. Now I'm looking at the body text to see what scores higher — the longer lines like \"This vibrant salad celebrates the earthy sweetness of roasted beets paired with tangy goat cheese\" exceed the 80-character length threshold and get filtered out, but the shorter subsequent lines might still be in play. I'm wondering if there's a longer candidate string that contains \"Roasted Beet and Goat Cheese Salad\" as a substring, which would cause it to be filtered out during deduplication. Let me trace through the actual content more carefully to see what's being returned. So the section label check is looking for an exact match in the SECTION_LABELS set, and `ingredients (serves 4)` doesn't match exactly even though \"ingredients\" is in there. Then I'm checking if it looks garbled—it starts with a capital letter and has multiple words, but \"serves\" is lowercase which triggers the garbled word detection.\n\nAfter stripping non-letters from \"serves\", it's 6 characters, so it's not actually garbled. This means `Ingredients (serves 4)` passes the hard filters and becomes a candidate, though it would score low for title-likeness. Now I'm looking more closely at the actual recipe titles like `Polenta with Wild Mushrooms` and `Roasted Beet and Goat Cheese Salad` to understand how they're