ith Wild Mushrooms\" anyway. And I'm realizing the embedding system might just be scoring \"Roasted Beet and Goat Cheese Salad\" higher when they're close, which I can't debug without seeing the actual wrong outputs.\n\nLet me focus on what I can actually identify. I'm going to compile the clear failure patterns I can spot.\n\nLooking at the test cases, I'm seeing a consistent issue: several recipes have ALL_CAPS titles in the source files but the expected output is in title case. BARSZCZ should be Barszcz, BEEF STEW should be Beef Stew, MUSHROOM PASTA should be Mushroom Pasta, and the same pattern repeats with MUSHROOM BARLEY SOUP, PLACKI SEROWE, PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE, and PAELLA VALENCIANA. I've seen enough examples to confirm this is a systematic problem rather than isolated cases.\n\nBut wait—I'm noticing something different in the other failing tests. Beet Salad, Coleslaw, Lemonade, Sernik, Szarlotka, Zupa Grzybowa, and Brownies are already in title case in the source files, not ALL_CAPS. So there are actually two different patterns here: some recipes start with ALL_CAPS titles that need to be converted to title case, while others are already in the correct format. I'm noticing a case mismatch with the chocolate brownies entries—the file has them in all caps when they should be in title case. There are also several OCR errors like the `1` corrupting \"Brûlée\" and missing reads for items like the chocolate hazelnut spread and lava cake. I need to continue checking the remaining entries. Continuing through the list, I'm seeing more inconsistencies—some items like Mushroom Pasta came through in all caps on the first line, while others like Ogrki Konserwowe didn't register at all. The split readings for Paella Valenciana and the garbage page interference with Piernik are particularly problematic, and there's a pattern where Polish names in all caps are being read when mixed case was expected. I'm continuing through the recipe list and noticing a pattern emerging—many of these OCR failures stem from garbage text appearing before the actual recipe title, which throws off the extraction logic.\n\nLooking at the `findBurstEnd` function, I see the issue: it only flags lines shorter than 20 characters as garbled, but some of this OCR noise is longer—like measurement fragments that contain special characters. These slip through the filter because they don't meet the length threshold, even though they're clearly corrupted text that shouldn't be part of the title. I see that the long garbage lines over 20 characters aren't being skipped, so they could become candidates for the title. But the `passesHardFilters` check catches the garbled one starting with lowercase `n`, and the ingredient-like line gets filtered out by the measurement pattern detection. Now I'm checking whether \"Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold\" passes the filters—it starts with uppercase so it's not garbled, but I need to see if it looks like an ingredient. The spam lines at the top pass burst detection because they're long enough, so the algorithm doesn't filter them out early. The actual title like \"Szarlotka\" appears much later in the document, around 70% through, which means it gets no position bonus. The spam candidates should score lower on title-likeness, but I need to verify whether \"Szarlotka\" itself passes the hard filters as a single mixed-case word.\n\nLooking at the garbled text detection: extracting just letters gives \"Szarlotka\" (9 characters), with a vowel ratio of 3/9 = 0.33, which passes. It's a single word without problematic case transitions or metadata patterns, so it's a valid candidate. Now I'm checking how the garbage lines compare.\n\nA cooking instruction like \"Beat egg whites until stiff peaks form, then fold\" passes the length filter but should score much lower on title-likeness since it's clearly instructional text. The issue might be that spam lines with high embedding scores are inflating the threshold beyond what \"Szarlotka\" can reach—maybe something like \"Season with salt, pepper, and nutmeg. Let simmer for\" is accidentally matching title patterns in embedding space, pushing the threshold too high.\n\nOr there's another possibility: \"Szarlotka\" might be getting filtered out earlier in the process. The pre-filter prioritizes candidates by whether they're all-caps and how short they are, so with many spam candidates competing for the top 25 slots, a single-word title could get pushed out before it even reaches the scoring stage.\n\nSorting candidates by capitalization and word count... Checking whether we actually generate enough candidates to trigger the sorting logic—with 35 spam lines each producing single-line and multi-line join candidates, plus filtering for lowercase starts and garbled text patterns, I need to trace through which ones survive to see if we hit that 25-candidate threshold for Szarlotka. Checking the remaining recipe lines against the filter logic — \"for\" is a common short word that should pass, and I'm verifying each line contains the right mix of word lengths and common articles to avoid being flagged as garbled text.\n\nLooking at the sorting behavior, the spam instruction lines are mostly multi-word phrases under 5 words, while \"Szarlotka\" is a single mixed-case word, so it would rank higher in the pre-filter results despite all these garbage lines technically passing through the validation checks.\n\nThe core issue is that these instruction lines inflate the candidate pool significantly, and some of them might actually score well in embedding space, which could either raise the threshold too high or prevent the actual title from ranking high enough since it's an uncommon single Polish word.\n\nMore likely though, `Szarlotka` is in the pool but the embedding model—probably English-biased—doesn't recognize it as the best title candidate. Meanwhile, generic recipe instructions like `Cool completely on a wire rack before serving` paradoxically score higher because they're semantically anchored in recipe-related content.\n\nI'm getting too speculative here. Let me focus on what I can actually verify: there's a clear pattern where OCR produces ALL_CAPS titles but the expected format is Title Case—like BARSZCZ becoming Barszcz, BEEF STEW becoming Beef Stew, and MUSHROOM PASTA becoming Mushroom Pasta.\n\nLooking at the full list now, I see this pattern extends across many entries: MUSHROOM BARLEY SOUP, PLACKI SEROWE, PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE, PAELLA VALENCIANA, and several Polish dishes with parenthetical descriptions like MAKOWIEC (Polish Poppy Seed Cake) and ŻUREK (Polish Sour Rye Soup). Some entries also have compound titles like CHOCOLATE BROWNIES + FUDGY CHOCOLATE BROWNIES that need consolidation.\n\nFor HERB BAKED SALMON, there's a deduplication issue where the compound title with DILL SAUCE VARIATION gets collapsed. And with PIEROGI RUSKIE, there's OCR garbage spillover from the previous page at the start of the file—the algorithm checks if lines are short and garbled to skip them, but these spillover lines are longer, so they don't get filtered out properly. The actual recipe title appears at line 18, but the garbage before it still gets processed.\n\nLooking at how the algorithm handles PIEROGI RUSKIE specifically: it's an ALL_CAPS line with 2 words and 14 characters, which qualifies for caps coalescing. The next line is the subtitle in mixed case, so only the title itself becomes a candidate. The algorithm then checks if the subtitle continues across multiple lines to determine if they should be grouped together. Żur and żytni split across lines would merge to `Żur żytni`, but that's case-mismatched from the expected `Żur Żytni`. For Zupy Zimowe Warzywne, the algorithm blocks joins starting from the section label, so it can only produce individual words or `Zimowe Warzywne`, missing the full three-word title. Paella Valenciana has a similar issue with capitalization across the line break.\n\nFor Bigos z Wdzonych Kielbas, the 2-line join gives `Bigos Wdzonych Kielbas`, but the expected title includes the preposition `z` that's either on the first line or missing from the OCR entirely.\n\nFor Lamb Stew, the word `Lamb` by itself passes the garbled check—it has 4 characters with a reasonable vowel ratio and doesn't exhibit the typical garbling patterns, so the 2-line join `Lamb Stew` should work fine.\n\nBut I'm puzzled why this is failing. Looking at what comes after these lines, there's a lot of generic filler text like \"A traditional recipe that celebrates...\" followed by section headers like `INGREDIENTS:`, which suggests the actual recipe content starts much later. The issue might be that the embedding score for `Lamb Stew` isn't strong enough despite the position factor, or there's something about how the filler text is being filtered that's affecting the candidate selection.\n\nActually, I think I see the real problem now—the deduplication logic might be removing `Lamb Stew` entirely. If `Lamb`, `Stew`, and `Lamb Stew` all pass the threshold, the dedup rule that keeps the shorter substring would eliminate `Lamb Stew` since it contains both `Lamb` and `Stew` as substrings. The dedup logic removes `Lamb Stew` because it's longer than the individual words, leaving just `Lamb + Stew` instead of the expected combined title. This same issue affects other split-title cases where short words are valid on their own. For the generic template files, I'm noticing that actual titles often appear deep in the document around 70-76% through, surrounded by OCR garbage and filler text.\n\nThe position bonus only helps candidates in the first half, so the real title gets no advantage. Worse, garbage lines like cooking instructions can artificially inflate the scoring threshold and outcompete the actual title. Some files have structural headers like `SEZON: WIOSNA` at the top in all caps that win over the real title due to their position bonus, and book chapter headers like `CHAPTER 4 - POLISH MAIN DISHES` similarly dominate the actual recipe title.\n\nNow I'm checking whether these headers pass the garbled text filters—the chapter header has mixed case and a digit in \"POL1SH,\" so it shouldn't be flagged as all caps, but I need to verify if it still passes the other structural checks. So the string passes the hard filters check, and it's not all caps so it wouldn't be treated as a structural heading. Now I'm checking whether \"Bigos Myśliwski\" on the line after the chapter header would be a strong candidate, but there's something failing in that evaluation.\n\nLooking at the actual file, the title itself appears clean despite OCR corruption elsewhere in the recipe body. The issue is that the pre-merge step is combining \"Bigos Myśliwski\" with the next line \"(Hunter's Stew)\" since parentheses are treated as continuation characters, resulting in the merged candidate \"Bigos Myśliwski (Hunter's Stew)\" instead of just the title alone. This is a case of the parenthetical subtitle being pulled in too aggressively. I'm looking at how the OCR digit substitution affects the garbling detection—specifically whether `isLikelyGarbled` correctly identifies `Crème Brû1ée` as corrupted when the `1` replaces an `l`. Let me trace through the logic to see if the function properly strips non-ASCII characters and detects this kind of substitution error. è` is non-ASCII, so `Crème` → `Crme`? Actually `è` → `/[^a-zA-Z]/` removes it → `Crme`. `Brû1ée` → `B`, `r`, non-ASCII `û`, digit `1`, non-ASCII `é`, `e` → `Bre`. So letters = `CrmeBre`. Hmm that's odd. Vowel ratio: `e`, `e` = 2/7 = 0.29 ✓. Actually this passes the garbled checks.\n\nBut `passesHardFilters(\"Crème Brû1ée\")` - the main issue: is it \"starts with lowercase\"? `Crème` starts with `C` (uppercase). Does it have `. ` + letter? No. So it passes.\n\nThe OCR text `Crème Brû1ée` doesn't match the expected `Crème Brûlée` because the algorithm returns the exact OCR output without correcting the corruption. For the Berry Jam example, `34  Berry Jam` gets filtered out by the number prefix check since it starts with a digit, but the actual title should just be `Berry Jam`.\n\nI'm realizing the algorithm can't extract `Berry Jam` as a standalone entry when it's embedded in `34  Berry Jam` on a single line. The header line `PRESERVES & JAMS` with the page number would be too long and filtered, leaving only the prefixed entry which then gets filtered by the number check. Any `Berry Jam` match would have to come from deeper in the recipe body text, which wouldn't be the right context.\n\nNow looking at the `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną` example—this should work since it's a clean title on its own line, but the garbling check is stripping non-ASCII characters like `ą` and `Ś`, leaving just the ASCII letters which might be throwing off the vowel count or other validation logic. So `ze` isn't in the common short words list—only `z` is—which means it gets flagged as garbled. The function correctly identifies \"Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną\" as failing the hard filters because of that suspicious two-letter word.\n\nThe real issue is that `ze` is a legitimate Polish preposition used before consonant clusters, but it's missing from the commonShort2 set. This same problem would affect any title containing `ze`, and likely other short Polish prepositions that aren't accounted for in the filter.\n\nLooking at how `buildCandidates` processes the text, it works on non-empty lines and joins consecutive ones together. For a title like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną` followed by body text, the function would create candidates by combining adjacent non-empty lines, but the length constraints and the garbled word check would still cause issues with that `ze` preposition. The 2-line join starting from the title would exceed the character limit, so no valid candidate emerges from the title itself. The algorithm would then fall back to other lines like the ingredients header, which I'm checking against the hard filters by normalizing it and testing whether it qualifies as a section label.\n\nThe core issue is that the garbled-word filter is incorrectly flagging the \"ze\" preposition, which prevents the actual title from being selected as a candidate. With no proper title candidate available, the algorithm ends up picking something incorrect like the section header instead. ybowy ze Śmietaną`, `Konfitury ze Liwek` — both blocked by the missing preposition. When titles span multiple lines like `Lamb` and `Stew`, the deduplication logic removes the compound form since it contains the individual words. Files with heavy OCR noise before the actual content create competing candidates that inflate the threshold, pushing the real title below the cutoff. And in some cases, season headers like `SEZON:` rank higher than the actual dish title.\n\nParenthetical subtitles get incorrectly merged into titles during the continuation step — things like `(Polish Gingerbread)` or `(Hunter's Stew)` shouldn't be joined to the main title. Similarly, compound titles with variation descriptions like `HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION` get stripped away by dedup because it contains the substring `DILL SAUCE VARIATION`.\n\nWhen titles span multiple lines, words in the SECTION_LABELS list like `Zupy` block the generation of multi-line joins entirely, so the full title never becomes a candidate. OCR errors also slip through — like `Crème Brû1ée` with a `1` instead of `l` — without any correction applied. And page numbers at the start of lines like `34  Berry Jam` fail the validation check, so the clean title never gets extracted.\n\nMissing prepositions in the OCR output create incomplete reconstructions, like `Bigos Wdzonych Kielbas` without the `z`. I'm now drafting the feedback analysis document to capture these patterns.\n\nBefore I finalize it, let me review the full list of failing cases to see if there are other patterns I've missed—things like `Polenta with Wild Mushrooms` which has a clean title but still fails, or the various Polish dishes with special characters and prepositions that might reveal a systematic issue. I'm seeing a clear pattern now—the main issues are title case mismatches, some OCR character substitutions, and problems with how multi-word titles get split and deduplicated. I have enough to write up the feedback document with these failure patterns identified.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7214,"cache_read_input_tokens":63199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7214},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a0bd2458-e6bc-4fcb-9e45-2dd61b6b2106","uuid":"d12f16c3-0e83-46f1-8d63-2d408ac30445"}
